04598nam a22007335i 9780748671502DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222011stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486715027 a10.1515/97807486715022doi  a(DE-B1597)615074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aP302.3 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401.4102852231 aPartington, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModern Diachronic Corpus-Assisted Discourse Studies :bCorpora Volume 5, Issue 2 /cAlan Partington. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tModern Diachronic Corpus-Assisted Discourse Studies (MD-CADS) on UK newspapers: an overview of the project -- tNewspaper discourse informalisation: a diachronic comparison from keywords -- tEvidence of evidentiality in the quality press 1993 and 2005 -- t‘The moral in the story’: a diachronic investigation of lexicalised morality in the UK press -- tInvestigating anti and some reflections on Modern Diachronic Corpus-Assisted Discourse Studies (MD-CADS) -- tScience in the news: a diachronic perspective0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume contains a collection of papers pertaining to the SiBol corpora, which consist of British broadsheet newspapers from the years 1993 and 2005. In order to examine diachronic variation, the papers compare the two sets of corpora using techniques such as keyword analyses, and targeted searches of terms like moral, ethics and science. The papers are from the field of Corpus-Assisted Discourse Studies (CADS) which combines a quantitative, statistical approach with a more qualitative approach typical of discourse analysis. Using such large corpora, the authors are able to study not only grammatical developments over time but also variations in lexical and phrasal preferences. This enables us to observe changes in newspaper prose style over the period (which reflect shifting relationships between newspapers and their readerships as well as perhaps overall changes in language) and also perform various sorts of content analyses, that is, examine new - and older - attitudes to social cultural and political phenomenon, as construed and projected by the mainstream UK quality (or ‘blacktop’) press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDiscourse analysisxData processing. 0aHistorical linguistics. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aClark, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuguid, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchi, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPartington, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864060740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074867150240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748671502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748671502/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK